        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Dollar cost averaging vs lump sum: Which is better mathematically?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Historically, lump sum investing outperforms dollar-cost averaging (DCA) approximately 68% of the time according to Vanguard. This is because stock markets tend to rise over the long term, so investing cash immediately gives it more time to compound. However, DCA provides a smoother ride and reduces the risk of investing everything right before a major crash."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does dollar cost averaging work in a bear market?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, DCA excels during bear markets or volatile periods. By investing a fixed amount on a regular schedule, you automatically purchase more shares when prices are low and fewer shares when prices are high. This lowers your average cost per share over time and provides psychological comfort when markets are dropping."
        }
